summary: For research purposes. Hypothetically, Tony gets kidnapped by hydra, and the Avengers come to save him. Is there a chaotic...
question: For research purposes. Hypothetically, Tony gets kidnapped by hydra, and the Avengers come to save him. Is there a chaotic neutral character that would help Tony escape because "idk man I work in my own self intrest and you alive would benifit me most" but that character isn't an/doesnt know the avengers?
answer:
It would probably be Jessica Jones, tbh. Hydra has its own abandoned buildings in New York, which they usually use for experiments or weapons trade-offs. Captives are more likely held in Eastern Europe, but the Avengers recognized the locations about two months after having a newly-recuperated Winter Soldier on their side. 

Look. Jessica was trying a shortcut because some low-life shit dad who wouldn’t pay child support was running. And she needed to catch him. Low-life shit dad then proceeded to trip and knock himself out. At least, she hoped that was all. So while she was waiting for him to wake up and realize that she had cuffed him to a bench–he wasn’t going anywhere until he explained why he was avoiding payments–she people-watched. 

Here’s the thing about people-watching; you learn a shit ton of information. You don’t even know you learn it until you hone it down, focus it. 

So five or so men passing by the old department store that got cut? Yeah, that screams suspicious. 

It’s embarrassingly easy to break in. She just does a little hop, skip, and a jump over into an open window, walks around a bit, and Tony Stark is unconscious on a chair. At least, at first. Then she sees his hand twitch a little bit, and she knows. He’s been in this situation probably dozens of times. 

“I’m not whoever the hell this is, Stark,” she mutters. “The fact that I’m going to cut you out of the restraints should say enough about that.” 

“That sounds like you’re authentic,” Tony says. “Hydra. Nabbed me while I was going back in a restaurant to get my takeout. Isn’t that the worst, going back to get it?” 

“Yeah,” she mutters. “Look, we gotta get out of here. They have men circling the building, and I’d really not like to have a charge about defacing public property or some shit. The police force hate me enough as it is. 

“Super?” he asks. Jessica snorts. 

“PI, occasional abilities that I use to my own advantage.” Tony Stark shrugs. 

“Fair enough.” 

He’s surprisingly…skilled. He finds scrap metal, tools, and builds a smoke bomb. 

“Should be fun,” he says with a grin. “Come on Jones, you wanna throw it?” 

They get the hell out, and Tony looks around. “Holy shit, I haven’t been around here since…five years ago. Shit.” 

“Seriously?” Jessica groans. “Do I have to take you home?” 

“It would be appreciated. I’d rather not become a Hydra tool again, if I can help it.” 

They ride on the subway, and Jessica tells everyone he’s just an Iron Man impersonator, and a pretty good one at that. Tony snorts, flipping through his phone. 

He says goodbye, Jessica walks back to her shit apartment, and thinks that it’ll be a good story to tell years from now. 

(The fact that she gets a damn good bottle of whiskey out of it–the kind that’s not even top shelf, it’s in a vault–means more to her.)

summary: I’m ambivalent about pepperony (I ship ironstrange, personally), but one of the things I love about it is that it throws out the...
body:
I’m ambivalent about pepperony (I ship ironstrange, personally), but one of the things I love about it is that it throws out the antiquated belief that people who are in true love are just perfect for each other from the get go. Tony and Pepper love each other, but he’s not perfect, and she demands change of him. Their relationship takes work, but that doesn’t make them not a good pair; rather, that demonstrates the strength of their commitment to each other. I may not ship it, but it’s pretty great for Marvel considering the fact that Sharon and Steve are a thing, despite the fact that they have never really talked and know like nothing about each other.

I guess what I’m trying to say is that it’s a ship I can appreciate for its significance and themes, even if the pairing isn’t my favorite.

title: Imagine:
body:
It was two days since you died, two days since your job finally took you with its risks. You were a police negotiator, you were the one always closes to the threat, watching the criminals in their eyes while trying to get them to surrender. You were doing just that two days ago, you were trying to stop a man from activating the bomb in the center of the Times Square only to die during the explosion. Now, you were buried in the casket in the same casket where you opened your eyes. You couldn’t breathe you couldn’t scream as loud as you wanted only hitting the casket from inside until you would die again and again until one day when you didn’t.  
You woke up in the white sterile room not understanding what was happening, even thinking that you died and maybe went to Heaven, but that thought quickly disappeared after one person walked inside; Tony Stark.

(gif not mine - taken from google)
